WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.200
Hi everybody, welcome to the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:10.200 --> 00:00:12.840
If you're joining for the first time, it's great to meet you.

00:00:12.840 --> 00:00:13.840
I'm Rachel.

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:16.320
I'm the host of the Hangout.

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:21.920
If this is your first Hangout, as I know it is for Wayne too, this is an open space for

00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:27.520
the whole data science community to connect and chat about data science leadership, questions

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:32.320
you're facing, and what's going on in the world of data science.

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:37.520
So as I mentioned, the sessions are recorded and shared to YouTube, as well as rstudio

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:38.799
data science Hangout site.

00:00:38.799 --> 00:00:44.060
So you can always go back and rewatch or find helpful resources there too.

00:00:44.060 --> 00:00:49.580
We always want to create spaces where everybody can participate and we can hear from everyone.

00:00:49.580 --> 00:00:52.799
So there's three ways that you can ask questions during these.

00:00:52.799 --> 00:00:57.400
So you can jump in live and raise your hand on Zoom.

00:00:58.279 --> 00:00:59.959
You can put questions in the Zoom chat.

00:00:59.959 --> 00:01:04.199
And feel free to put a little star next to it if you want me to read the question for

00:01:04.199 --> 00:01:06.839
you if maybe it's a little loud where you are.

00:01:06.839 --> 00:01:12.760
But we also have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously too, and Tyler will

00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:13.760
share that.

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:17.199
She was right ahead of me and shared it just in the chat.

00:01:17.199 --> 00:01:22.919
I just always like to reiterate, we love to hear from everybody, no matter your level

00:01:22.919 --> 00:01:25.919
of experience or area of work too.

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:32.639
But today I am so happy to be joined by my co-host, Wayne Jones, Principal Data Scientist

00:01:32.639 --> 00:01:34.599
at Shell.

00:01:34.599 --> 00:01:38.040
And Wayne, typically we get these started with just having you introduce yourself a

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:42.279
little bit and sharing a bit about the work that you do.

00:01:42.279 --> 00:01:44.320
So my name is Wayne Jones.

00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:46.400
I'm a Principal Data Scientist in Shell.

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:50.199
I've been there now for 15 years.

00:01:50.239 --> 00:01:56.440
Prior to that, my background has been in ecological modelling.

00:01:56.440 --> 00:01:59.400
So my PhD was in modelling the growth of fish.

00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:07.080
And following that, I went to work for an energy company, EDF, as a quantum analyst.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:10.960
And then I went to work as a pricing consultancy for about five or six years.

00:02:10.960 --> 00:02:16.960
Then I've been at Shell for 15 years now.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:21.919
I would say most of the time I've been the role of a statistical consultant and as such,

00:02:21.919 --> 00:02:28.520
you get exposed to lots and lots of different business problems across all manner of areas.

00:02:28.520 --> 00:02:34.679
For some, people might find quite surprising, given that I'm working for an energy company.

00:02:34.679 --> 00:02:39.960
So, you know, I would say certainly in the earlier years, a lot of my time has been spent

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:45.759
developing open source software for environmental monitoring applications.

00:02:45.759 --> 00:02:46.919
Yeah.

00:02:46.919 --> 00:02:48.360
Awesome.

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:55.320
Yeah, I think it'd be helpful too for everyone to understand a little bit more of what you do.

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:59.600
I love the example of how you're using open source across the industry.

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:05.600
And would you be able to share a little bit more about the work that you're doing there?

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:06.360
Yeah, sure.

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:09.639
I mean, I was hoping to do it more formally at some point in the future.

00:03:09.639 --> 00:03:11.240
And perhaps one of the meetups as well.

00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:13.399
So I can certainly give more details there, right.

00:03:13.399 --> 00:03:21.960
But groundwater monitoring is something that is a very open and transparent industry,

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:29.279
basically, where we work with environmental regulators and we periodically monitor our sites,

00:03:29.279 --> 00:03:35.039
whether it be petrol stations or refineries or terminals.

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:43.960
And we have and we report out the latest status to the environmental regulators

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:49.279
and we work with them to develop the best solutions for remediation,

00:03:49.279 --> 00:03:51.240
if there are any issues effectively.

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:58.919
Right now, this is something that we work with a range of different environmental engineering companies as consultants.

00:03:58.919 --> 00:04:04.360
And they perhaps go out and do the sampling of the data, do the send the data to the lab,

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:06.559
get concentration results back.

00:04:06.559 --> 00:04:12.399
And then in the past, there was lots of different ways of analysing the same data.

00:04:12.399 --> 00:04:17.440
So there's an opportunity to standardise, make things even easier for everyone

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:22.119
and to increase the level of interpretability from these data sets.

00:04:22.119 --> 00:04:31.160
Right. So this is this basically created in collaboration with the University of Glasgow, an application called GWSDAT.

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:40.440
It's available as an R package, GWSDAT stands for Groundwater Spatial Temporal Data Analysis Tool.

00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:44.200
You guys can just download and it's free to use effectively.

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:49.119
Yeah, and it's all to summarise what it does effectively.

00:04:49.119 --> 00:04:57.399
It's there to identify trends in groundwater solid concentrations.

00:04:57.440 --> 00:05:01.279
Thanks, Wayne. I'll share that in the chat window, too.

00:05:01.279 --> 00:05:05.600
I just thought it's really important for people to to understand about as well,

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:11.519
because I think you've done an amazing job building the community around that, too.

00:05:11.519 --> 00:05:22.839
But I'd love to ask you and maybe kick off some of the questions with what's something that you're most excited about with regards to data science in the next year or so?

00:05:22.839 --> 00:05:29.440
Wow, that's a good question, actually. I can't really say a lot.

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:39.760
I mean, I suppose the most exciting thing I've done recently is I've been working on a bid with offshore wind.

00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:45.200
Right. So the Dutch government, for example, they have for each offshore wind site,

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:50.760
they have different criteria for winning that bid effectively.

00:05:50.760 --> 00:06:00.600
And the one I was working on was on environmental and ecological aspects of having a wind farm.

00:06:00.600 --> 00:06:04.440
How do you avoid bird strike, for example? How do you keep noise down?

00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:12.239
How do you monitor the environment? How do you demonstrate that you've had a net positive impact on the environment as well?

00:06:12.239 --> 00:06:20.399
And this kind of brought me back to my ecological modelling days and it was really good.

00:06:20.399 --> 00:06:27.839
I can't give full details of the kind of stuff we're proposing as part of the bid, but I have to say it's very, very exciting.

00:06:27.839 --> 00:06:34.320
Yeah. And again, we'll be done in a very, if successful in the bid, it will be very open and transparent.

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:44.959
So we'll be looking to develop open source solutions and also, you know, being open with data.

00:06:44.959 --> 00:06:51.600
Well, while people are thinking of their own questions, I get the luxury of being able to ask you the questions that I want.

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:58.920
So I would love to hear a little bit about how you've advocated for open source across the company

00:06:58.920 --> 00:07:04.600
and how you've kind of gotten people comfortable with the idea of open source.

00:07:04.600 --> 00:07:08.399
Well, yeah, that's another good question, right?

00:07:08.399 --> 00:07:18.160
I would say I'll give you an example on that one. Given I've been in Shell for a long time, when we first started,

00:07:18.160 --> 00:07:21.679
not only did we, so let me roll it back a little bit, right?

00:07:21.679 --> 00:07:27.920
So when we first started using open source tools, we were actually challenged, right?

00:07:27.920 --> 00:07:33.880
I remember speaking to an architect in Shell and him saying, don't bother investing in open source tools, Wayne,

00:07:33.880 --> 00:07:37.600
because they'll probably be banned by Shell in a couple of years time, right?

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:43.559
I mean, I look at how the future's panned out. It couldn't be any different, right?

00:07:43.559 --> 00:07:52.799
We use lots of open source tools like R and Python in our jobs on a day to day basis now.

00:07:52.799 --> 00:08:02.359
I suppose, you know, what we're advocating in terms of open source, how I've advocated it is by demonstrating the success of our GWS app, right?

00:08:02.359 --> 00:08:10.679
And there's a will, I would say scientists really like the idea of making their code open source.

00:08:10.679 --> 00:08:16.559
So quite a few people come to me and ask for the pros and cons of doing it, right?

00:08:16.559 --> 00:08:22.959
Now, for GWS app, the business case for being open source is fairly open and shut, right?

00:08:22.959 --> 00:08:28.320
You know, it's basically it's open, transparent, you know, environment regulators haven't got a hell of a lot of money.

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:33.359
They're not going to trust black box solutions. So it's an open and shut case.

00:08:33.359 --> 00:08:43.000
But then, but we're expanding now and our business leaders are opening their eyes to the benefits of being open source,

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:52.440
for perhaps in the future, we didn't see the benefit that we have now. It's becoming a more open culture.

00:08:52.440 --> 00:08:59.200
That's great. Thank you. I see a lot of questions coming in now, both on Slido and through the chat.

00:08:59.200 --> 00:09:08.000
Joe, I see you put a question into the chat. Would you want to jump in?

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.200
Oh, sure. Thanks. Took me a minute to unmute. No worries.

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:17.880
Yeah, I'm curious when you talk about standardizing tools, who's responsible for doing that?

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:28.200
And, you know, are there are there examples out there of effectively standardizing tools for monitoring environmental impact?

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:36.119
So, yeah. So first of all, it's a global industry.

00:09:36.119 --> 00:09:42.359
So we do this across the different globes and there's different standards in different areas of the globe.

00:09:42.359 --> 00:09:50.359
Right. A lot. There are many, many industry bodies that advocate best practice in these areas.

00:09:50.359 --> 00:09:59.000
Right. And you'll see in the list of references where we are actually referencing best guidance, get best guidance documents.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:09.400
And this, if you like, is the kind of document which outlines statistical techniques in a digestible fashion to environmental engineers.

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:25.159
Yeah. So, you know, it's those kind of best practices, those kind of industry bodies was helping the standardization and the level of interpretation of this kind of data set.

00:10:25.159 --> 00:10:30.159
In other countries. Right. It's not quite as developed. All right.

00:10:30.159 --> 00:10:33.840
And that's one of the things I'm particularly proud of with Julio Vestat. Right.

00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:39.479
You know, is that because it's open source, there's no barriers to its use and it gets used globally.

00:10:39.479 --> 00:10:44.520
Right. It gets used. You know, I'm really, really surprised by the way it gets used.

00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:49.559
So the last person who joined the Julio Vestat group on LinkedIn is from Yemen.

00:10:49.559 --> 00:10:56.440
Right. We've got people from, you know, all over the globe, Australia, America, you know, especially America.

00:10:56.440 --> 00:11:01.719
Right. But then, you know, you're talking like Malta, China, Pakistan.

00:11:01.719 --> 00:11:10.080
You know, it truly is a global tool. So that's one of the things I'm most proud about.

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:13.880
Amazing. Wayne, random question for you.

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:18.039
Do you happen to have a blind right in front of you that you could close?

00:11:18.039 --> 00:11:24.400
We can't see part of the face sometimes.

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:29.679
Works a bit better. So work a bit better. A bit better.

00:11:29.679 --> 00:11:34.880
Yes. There we go. OK, perfect. Thank you.

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:40.440
Move on, guys. I see you also just put a question to the chat if you want to jump in.

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:44.080
Hi, Rachel. And hi, everybody. Thank you so much, Rachel, for the chance.

00:11:44.080 --> 00:11:53.320
Wayne, I'd just like to find out if your shiny app is built using Golem, the package Golem.

00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:58.799
Oh, do you know what? I've never heard of Golem, if I'm honest here.

00:11:58.799 --> 00:12:02.280
Maybe you can tell me a bit about it. So obviously I haven't heard about it.

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:08.440
It's just not written using Golem. I think Golem packages.

00:12:08.440 --> 00:12:13.520
It's a similar paradigm to the question that Joe asked, right, about standardization.

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:26.039
So it's a package that allows you to develop shiny apps using a standard method that essentially Colin Faye says the app,

00:12:26.039 --> 00:12:33.479
the Golem allows you to build industrial shiny apps that are robust.

00:12:33.479 --> 00:12:38.080
So he has a certain methodology that you follow in Golem to build a shiny app.

00:12:38.080 --> 00:12:45.679
So I was just wondering if that's what was used to build this app.

00:12:45.679 --> 00:12:51.159
Well, it isn't. And I will certainly check out Golem because it sounds very interesting.

00:12:51.159 --> 00:13:02.359
Right. It might not have been around when we were doing this, to be fair, because it's quite a while ago since we first developed this version of Jira Vesta.

00:13:02.359 --> 00:13:07.479
I can see why Golem's been built. Right. Because, you know.

00:13:07.479 --> 00:13:13.039
Shiny is absolutely fantastic for the smaller apps. Right.

00:13:13.039 --> 00:13:25.919
But the large, big industrial apps, sometimes if you don't design it properly, it can become rather unwieldy and very hard to support and maintain.

00:13:25.919 --> 00:13:38.119
You know, and that's really important in the spirit of open source is to make it a way that someone can come and run with it for themselves.

00:13:38.119 --> 00:13:49.119
But, you know, if it's a big cluster of different functions in R and shiny, which is not particularly well designed, then doing that is very, very hard.

00:13:49.119 --> 00:13:54.159
So I will certainly check out Golem for future shiny applications.

00:13:54.159 --> 00:13:58.239
And thanks for that. Thanks, Vimanka.

00:13:58.239 --> 00:14:01.679
I see there's a few anonymous questions, too, on Slido, Wayne.

00:14:01.679 --> 00:14:10.880
And one was what have been some of the biggest changes in open source data science in your last 15 years with Shell?

00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:23.599
Yeah, I mean, that's a good first of all, I would say it's been the adoption to begin with of open source science, open source tools.

00:14:23.599 --> 00:14:32.880
And if I roll it back even further, you know, when we would do when I was in university to a PhD, it was an old fashioned computer lab.

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:36.559
And we had the old Unix machines. Right.

00:14:36.559 --> 00:14:41.760
And they were, I think, about £20,000 each. And that's over 20 years ago now.

00:14:41.760 --> 00:14:48.239
Right. And then you also I wasn't about you had something called S plus instead.

00:14:48.239 --> 00:14:52.039
Right. And the license was about £20,000 a year and the rest of it.

00:14:52.039 --> 00:15:02.640
Right. So but within the time that I had finished my PhD, we'd moved to Linux, which meant you could install on just using standard PCs,

00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:06.599
which obviously saved about, you know, £19,000 per PC.

00:15:06.599 --> 00:15:11.640
And we had started using our saved all the license costs for S plus and all.

00:15:11.640 --> 00:15:16.880
So that's that's going back. That's a long way. And that saves a maths department lots of money.

00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:21.919
So it probably could keep on more staff as a consequence of that. Right.

00:15:21.919 --> 00:15:31.719
And all the benefits. Coming back to Shell now, you know, I see changes from my perspective is first of all,

00:15:31.719 --> 00:15:36.400
there was a reluctance to adopt open source software.

00:15:36.400 --> 00:15:43.919
Right. So, you know, talk discussions of those architects, but they just didn't trust it from an architectural security perspective.

00:15:43.919 --> 00:15:47.599
Right. And some of them fears could still be warranted now.

00:15:47.599 --> 00:15:55.479
Right. But there's also about the the technical correctness of the underlying outcomes as well.

00:15:55.479 --> 00:16:01.760
Right. So in the past, I've done work in R and we've had to double check it in SAS.

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:08.640
Right. OK, because the people that traditionally did this didn't really trust that it's still a new kid on the block.

00:16:08.640 --> 00:16:18.080
Right. But then in my experience, because I have such a large user base, then lots of the functionality gets a hell of a lot of testers.

00:16:18.080 --> 00:16:25.760
Right. And you don't, you know, and generally speaking, especially for the packages which have been used high, high volume.

00:16:25.760 --> 00:16:36.000
It's very, very mathematically correct. Indeed, I've seen mistakes in some commercial offerings of software because they're just not tested to the same amount.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:49.359
So then there's the adoption of open source and then there's the actually making open source of, you know, stories like me where, you know, we don't have this very protective business model.

00:16:49.359 --> 00:16:52.320
Right. We realise that there's benefits in doing open source software.

00:16:52.320 --> 00:16:55.960
Do you notice that as a benefit is one example of that as well.

00:16:55.960 --> 00:17:06.000
So not only are we using open source tools, we're giving back to the open source community now as well, engaging the open source community.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:25.920
Thank you, Wayne. Another anonymous question that was there was, do you see new types and categories of use cases where machine learning or methods are particularly useful in providing a solution like better predictions or classification example?

00:17:26.920 --> 00:17:30.599
So new, new types of machine learning. And can you repeat?

00:17:30.599 --> 00:17:42.760
I think. Yeah, sorry. It was a little bit of a longer question. Do you see new types of use cases where machine learning methods are particularly useful in providing a solution?

00:17:42.760 --> 00:17:51.000
Yeah. So, I mean, Shell's business model is it's completely changing.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:18:00.760
Right. You know, there is an energy transition and more and more and more I'm involved in what we refer to as renewable energy solutions problems.

00:18:00.760 --> 00:18:10.439
Right. So this is related to low carbon technologies such as wind, solar, carbon sequestration projects.

00:18:10.439 --> 00:18:23.319
And these are all fairly new right now. And it's and the scale and the speed at which developments are happening in this space are quite, quite surprising.

00:18:23.319 --> 00:18:29.479
Right. So all the machine learning technologies are being used to a lesser or greater degree.

00:18:29.479 --> 00:18:38.000
Right. You know, we say we're using all manner of technologies, whether it be basic, simple time series forecasting.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:46.439
Machine vision is also a strong one. So that's the deep learning. LSTMs when it comes to solar forecasting.

00:18:46.439 --> 00:18:53.160
Look at all. When I first started in Shell, right, I was almost a heretic for bringing to the table random forest.

00:18:53.160 --> 00:19:01.439
Right. But then now and now again, why don't we, you know, random forest and machine learning algorithms such as that are becoming part of the course as well.

00:19:01.439 --> 00:19:08.920
Another big use case that we have and I suppose a big ticket item is predictive maintenance.

00:19:08.920 --> 00:19:20.479
Right. This is where we listen to the data continuously streaming, look out for anomalies and warn people when we think components are about to fail.

00:19:20.479 --> 00:19:26.439
So you can plan for failure and reacting to failures when they actually occur.

00:19:26.439 --> 00:19:30.599
So the answer to your question is loads. Right.

00:19:30.599 --> 00:19:34.479
Then I mean, I could keep on going for a long, long time.

00:19:34.479 --> 00:19:46.119
Right. There's loads of different new and novel applications coming in and in need and are mostly associated with the transition in the energy.

00:19:46.119 --> 00:19:55.719
Thank you, Wayne. There are a lot of questions coming in about like using open source at Shell and and how you are able to advocate for that.

00:19:55.719 --> 00:20:05.880
And so I want to say if other people are experiencing this, too, and want to jump in the conversation, feel free to jump into and raise your hand.

00:20:05.880 --> 00:20:12.959
One of the questions was you said your leaders are much more supportive of open source because they're recognizing the benefits.

00:20:12.959 --> 00:20:19.959
What benefits exactly are they most vocal about? Goodness.

00:20:19.959 --> 00:20:25.959
Right. OK, so I mean, I guess it has to do with the themes around machine learning and AI.

00:20:25.959 --> 00:20:41.880
Right. Back in the day, you know, when I was this consultant in Shell, we were rather a niche and there wasn't the general IT support for us.

00:20:41.880 --> 00:20:46.199
Right. So we typically did skunk projects, basically.

00:20:46.199 --> 00:20:52.040
Right. And we just had our own IT infrastructure and all the rest of it.

00:20:52.040 --> 00:20:58.719
But now, you know, it's completely gone, you know, huge scale.

00:20:58.719 --> 00:21:05.520
Right. And Shell as a business, and I'm sure lots of other businesses as well.

00:21:05.520 --> 00:21:08.800
We have the IT departments basically working with us now.

00:21:08.800 --> 00:21:15.119
Right. Supporting us in our endeavours because they can see the benefits of it as well.

00:21:15.119 --> 00:21:25.760
Right. And I would say things like Python and R, they understand the benefits of deploying these open source solutions,

00:21:25.760 --> 00:21:30.400
the capabilities and their machine learning and an AI, for example.

00:21:30.400 --> 00:21:34.839
Right. So and indeed, it's the chosen method to go.

00:21:34.839 --> 00:21:43.000
If you didn't, you know, if you didn't go open source, there wouldn't be a hell of a lot of choice out there either for that matter.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:54.479
So it's it's it's really been revolutionary. I'm talking about the last 10 years, I would say, not just recently.

00:21:54.520 --> 00:21:59.800
Thanks, Wayne. I see, Joey, you had a follow up question to this as well.

00:21:59.800 --> 00:22:05.920
Do you want to jump in? Yeah, I guess.

00:22:05.920 --> 00:22:12.520
Thanks. Already answered the first half of my question, but I guess I'll follow up more specifically.

00:22:12.520 --> 00:22:26.560
How do you get around the. The topic of lost revenue to when we see so many companies out there making money off of proprietary methods.

00:22:26.560 --> 00:22:32.640
Really, a follow up on the last question, what are the most persuasive arguments that you've used or seen?

00:22:32.640 --> 00:22:44.199
To to advocate for the adoption of open source. Well, I guess I'll use again that as an example, I two reasons.

00:22:44.199 --> 00:22:50.760
Right. Is one. It's transparent.

00:22:50.760 --> 00:22:58.640
Right. And we're not hiding anything. Right. Because if you have have if your company is selling your software,

00:22:58.640 --> 00:23:04.000
then you're not going to give your IP away by giving letting people see underneath the hood.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:08.719
Right. And the second one is cost. Right.

00:23:08.719 --> 00:23:15.439
So and in the case you start working right, the environmental regulators were saying this is open source.

00:23:15.439 --> 00:23:19.479
We're making it publicly available so that other people can use it as well.

00:23:19.479 --> 00:23:26.319
So there's greater adoption. Greater adoption means better the more you trust it.

00:23:26.319 --> 00:23:31.680
Basically, the fact it's open source is nothing to hide or demonstrate completely what's underneath the hood.

00:23:31.680 --> 00:23:37.160
It's all visible to see. So you build that trust and also trees to use.

00:23:37.160 --> 00:23:44.599
So there's no barriers to such as environmental regulators using it for themselves.

00:23:44.599 --> 00:23:57.640
So certainly in my scenario, that's where we see the biggest benefits of having, you know, using and distributing open source software.

00:23:57.640 --> 00:24:03.599
In other areas, it could be a bit of a gray area, right? You know, you have to and my steer has always been,

00:24:03.599 --> 00:24:09.880
you've got to make that business case bulletproof before you go and open source your software.

00:24:10.119 --> 00:24:15.599
Because one thing I would say about it is that it is a one way street.

00:24:15.599 --> 00:24:19.760
Right. Once you made it open source, you can't recover it back.

00:24:19.760 --> 00:24:31.199
So you better make damn sure when you do make it open sources for the right reasons and you have clearance from the business to do.

00:24:31.199 --> 00:24:39.680
