00:34:12.439 --> 00:34:18.239
Yeah. Wayne, I remember when we were chatting, maybe this was a few months ago now,

00:34:18.239 --> 00:34:26.360
but you talked a bit about how you collaborate with Excel users, too.

00:34:26.360 --> 00:34:36.120
And I'd love to hear a little bit more about that or best practices that you have for people who are working with all kinds of different data people.

00:34:36.120 --> 00:34:41.679
And maybe they don't use use our Python. Yeah, that's a good that's a good question.

00:34:41.679 --> 00:34:50.959
Right. I mean, because. When we designed Gilead Restart, you know, it was in in mind that it's not a statistician,

00:34:50.959 --> 00:34:54.800
it's not our programmers that are going to be using it, it's environmental engineers.

00:34:54.800 --> 00:34:59.760
Right. And we wanted the barrier of entry to be as low as possible.

00:34:59.760 --> 00:35:07.679
OK, so the primary user interface for Gilead Restart as it was designed in the first instance is an Excel add-in effectively.

00:35:07.679 --> 00:35:20.959
Right. Where users have an Excel add-in menu which behind the scenes connects with R, grabs the data,

00:35:20.959 --> 00:35:27.280
sends it to R, uses Gilead Restart package and uses Shiny to give you the graphical interface.

00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:35.120
So, you know, no one has that do any R programming effectively, it's a point and click.

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:40.639
What you see is what you get kind of interface. Yeah. However, the code is openly available.

00:35:40.639 --> 00:35:47.639
We do have pull requests from environmental engineers, you know, who wanted something updated in the software and all the rest of it.

00:35:47.639 --> 00:35:55.320
So it works. It really does work in that respect. Yeah. So good question.

00:35:55.320 --> 00:36:01.000
There are a few hacks in the background to make it work in Excel, right?

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:13.520
Effectively, how it works is in Excel, it takes the settings and the data and puts it into a temporary set of CSV files and temporary notepad file.

00:36:13.520 --> 00:36:20.760
And then it uses it, looks at the registry to see where R lives and then it uses R in batch mode.

00:36:20.760 --> 00:36:28.040
Right. So grab the temporary files and run Excel and run Shiny in the Gilead Restart package like so.

00:36:28.040 --> 00:36:37.479
Yeah. So they don't, that's how we, that's our little trick for getting it to work in the background effectively.

00:36:37.479 --> 00:36:42.560
I know that's something that has come up quite a bit on like past calls or meetups too.

00:36:42.560 --> 00:36:49.199
So how did you communicate with people how to use this effectively?

00:36:49.199 --> 00:36:54.639
Say that again, sorry. Like for example, thinking of the Excel user who's going to use it.

00:36:54.639 --> 00:36:59.439
How did you communicate with different stakeholders how they should use the tool?

00:36:59.439 --> 00:37:08.760
Yeah, well, I think, you know, the reason we used Excel to begin with is because they all managed their data in Excel anyway.

00:37:08.760 --> 00:37:14.879
Right. And prior to Gilead Restart, you know, they were doing the analysis typically in Excel.

00:37:14.879 --> 00:37:25.360
Right. You know, one of the, one of the benefits in using Gilead Restart is not the sophisticated trend detection is sometimes just a simple plotting functionality.

00:37:25.360 --> 00:37:31.040
Right. You know, building a three by three plot in Excel might take you all day.

00:37:31.040 --> 00:37:39.959
Right. Whereas you could do it in Shiny Gilead Restart interface, you know, in a couple of clicks, just for a couple of clicks.

00:37:39.959 --> 00:37:47.320
In our case, you know, Excel was the natural entry point, OK, because that's where people used it.

00:37:47.320 --> 00:37:54.639
Right. And in terms of in terms of how they used it, we did it with a combination of we have a user manual.

00:37:54.639 --> 00:38:04.800
Right. And we have webinars and whenever people ask for help, we can we can step in and give them introductions and all the rest of it.

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:08.080
We are in the process of actually coming up with some videos.

00:38:08.080 --> 00:38:13.719
Right. University of Glasgow student Peter there is looking to create some videos at the moment as well.

00:38:13.719 --> 00:38:23.800
Yeah. I would say training is probably our weakest point at the moment, I would say.

00:38:23.800 --> 00:38:29.239
It's getting to the point where we've got lots and lots of users now and people are crying out for training.

00:38:30.080 --> 00:38:36.360
Now, we don't have the time. I mean, and this is perhaps one of the bad things about open source software, right?

00:38:36.360 --> 00:38:39.800
Because there's no because we don't charge a license fee.

00:38:39.800 --> 00:38:45.320
We want to go, you know, it's only our own time that's going into this.

00:38:45.320 --> 00:38:50.479
So providing training is expensive, time consuming.

00:38:50.479 --> 00:38:57.040
Right. And we don't get, you know, there's no cost model there to recover it effectively.

00:38:57.040 --> 00:39:04.399
So I'd say maybe that. So what we're trying to do is come up with a basic set of training videos that we can share and are open to everyone.

00:39:04.399 --> 00:39:14.000
You know, you know, maybe that's one of the negative things about being an open source that it doesn't generate the revenue to provide training, for example.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:20.320
Right. Yeah. One point.

