What skills do you tell technical leaders to focus on?

00:47:44.360 --> 00:47:49.639
Are there people you're mentoring? Yeah, I mean, it very much depends on the domain, right?

00:47:49.639 --> 00:47:56.479
So, you know, being a principal science expert in Shell, you know, you're talking about a very diverse set of skills.

00:47:56.479 --> 00:48:02.239
Right. So we've got lots of chemists as well, geologists, data scientists.

00:48:02.239 --> 00:48:13.639
So why tell people if they want to go down the technical career path is to just soak it all up, right?

00:48:13.639 --> 00:48:20.800
The best you can, right? Because as you go perhaps further into your career, maybe further up the food chain, right?

00:48:20.800 --> 00:48:27.399
You get less time to do technical work, right? You seem to get dragged in other directions, right?

00:48:27.399 --> 00:48:32.280
So when you're early on in your career, you know, like doing a PhD as well.

00:48:32.280 --> 00:48:36.159
Right. You have a lot of time to do technical work.

00:48:36.159 --> 00:48:41.040
So soak it up, kids, you know, and use your initiative.

00:48:41.040 --> 00:48:46.879
You know, there's lots of training material to do whatever you want to do out there now.

00:48:46.879 --> 00:48:52.320
Right. It's not like, you know, years and years ago when, you know, everybody had to go to the library for books and stuff like that.

00:48:52.760 --> 00:48:58.719
YouTube and it'll tell you four or five different ways to explain the same problem.

00:48:58.719 --> 00:49:02.120
I'll give you an example of using initiative, right?

00:49:02.120 --> 00:49:10.040
You know, we bought some, this is going back again, we bought some new PCs, ran some algorithms, realised they weren't running any quicker.

00:49:10.040 --> 00:49:15.399
Right. And I was like, why not? Well, the reason is because even the PC was quicker, more powerful.

00:49:15.399 --> 00:49:19.120
It's by virtue of it had more cores.

00:49:19.120 --> 00:49:22.719
Right. But each core was the same sort of processing power.

00:49:22.719 --> 00:49:32.239
So some of the algorithms we were using were, they were just single threaded, just multi-threaded, whereas, you know, we wanted to move to multi-threaded.

00:49:32.239 --> 00:49:36.399
So I used a look just on my own back, right?

00:49:36.399 --> 00:49:44.639
I looked into parallel processing in R and then when we actually had some more use cases in R, I started using this parallel processing.

00:49:44.639 --> 00:49:47.639
Right. That got me noticed for some of the guys.

00:49:47.639 --> 00:49:52.959
And then when Spark came in, I was the person to do the pilot with Spark app, for example.

00:49:52.959 --> 00:49:59.159
And it ended up with me and the now VP, you know, on a Spark conference explaining what was done there.

00:49:59.159 --> 00:50:02.879
So that's just one example of using initiative. Don't hold back.

00:50:02.879 --> 00:50:07.679
I don't wait. Just do it.

00:50:07.679 --> 00:50:12.639
Like that, I was writing that down using your initiative.

00:50:12.639 --> 00:50:17.199
Santiago, I see you put a question into the chat. You want to jump in?

