00:50:38.840 --> 00:50:49.879
Yeah, this is. Yeah, I mean, in terms of, you know, what I'd be looking for is good technical depth.

00:50:49.879 --> 00:50:59.800
Right. But also, you know, if you're working in industry as well, you need to you need to be able to explain and communicate yourself as well.

00:50:59.800 --> 00:51:05.639
And this is perhaps somewhere where the data scientists could learn a bit more.

00:51:05.639 --> 00:51:14.959
You know, still go to conferences and see you really, really badly presented presentations are very, very good pieces of work.

00:51:14.959 --> 00:51:19.479
And I think in industry, you know, a real benefit if you can.

00:51:19.479 --> 00:51:30.679
If you can be both technically good and also very good at communicating these often complex principles to non-mathematicians as well.

00:51:30.679 --> 00:51:37.919
Yeah. So and often these skills are kind of mutually exclusive or compete with one another effectively.

00:51:37.919 --> 00:51:46.399
It's hard to get a combination of those two things together effectively.

00:51:46.399 --> 00:51:58.719
And as for the interview process. Right. I think some of my colleagues advocate doing, you know, programming tests or analytical tests before.

00:51:59.239 --> 00:52:08.320
Some people actually swear by them, to be fair. Right. But had that been the case, I probably wouldn't have got into Shell because I'm not very good at tests like that.

00:52:08.320 --> 00:52:15.600
But what is the right. So I for that reason, I'm not so enamoured with these tests.

00:52:15.600 --> 00:52:25.919
You know, I think you just get a good feel. On with a candidate, you know, when you talk to him, when you start talking about technical stuff,

00:52:25.919 --> 00:52:33.919
you get an idea quite quickly whether that person knows what he or she is talking about.

