00:53:20.600 --> 00:53:30.040
Yeah. And for someone so, you know, if you spot someone who you think is really good at communicating.

00:53:30.040 --> 00:53:36.320
Right. And you're impressed by them, you know, just buddy up. Right. Say, look, I like the way you did that.

00:53:36.320 --> 00:53:41.479
Can you give me some hints and tips as to how you do it? Right. And often there's the basic stuff as well.

00:53:41.479 --> 00:53:52.320
Like, you know, the trouble is that data science, you kind of focus on a very small area sometimes and you get kind of obsessed by the details.

00:53:52.320 --> 00:53:59.800
Right. I think I've done a presentation about data storytelling in the past.

00:53:59.800 --> 00:54:06.239
Right. And one of the first things I had, I advocate is to step back, step back, step back some more.

00:54:06.239 --> 00:54:20.879
So when you're presenting a problem, you give the bigger picture and you narrow in to the data science, technical details rather than rather than actually, you know, obsessing about the details immediately.

00:54:20.879 --> 00:54:26.760
You've got to bring the people in. And the other thing I would say is empathy.

00:54:26.760 --> 00:54:34.479
Right. If you think more empathically. Right. Then that will go a long way.

00:54:34.520 --> 00:54:44.040
So instead of thinking about it from a data science, put yourself in the in the customers or the client's shoes and think about it from their perspective.

00:54:44.040 --> 00:54:52.040
That really helps. Right. Really helps. Those are my two tips.

